108
00:06:41,700 --> 00:06:44,120
I like to have some level of
consideration toward my students,

109
00:06:44,120 --> 00:06:46,500
so instead of saying what I'd like to say to you now...

110
00:06:47,200 --> 00:06:51,260
I will be very grateful if you could guess what I want to say.

111
00:06:51,760 --> 00:06:54,470
For some reason, I just made a pretty good guess.

112
00:06:54,800 --> 00:06:57,390
Very well. Please listen then.

113
00:06:58,210 --> 00:07:00,240
This is about when I was grading these tests.

114
00:07:03,200 --> 00:07:05,260
And next up is...

115
00:07:06,000 --> 00:07:06,920
Arashiyama?!

116
00:07:07,090 --> 00:07:08,730
It happens every time.

117
00:07:09,180 --> 00:07:13,360
When it's Arashiyama's turn, I get a sinking feeling in my stomach.

118
00:07:16,790 --> 00:07:20,560
She blatantly gives up while answering the question,

119
00:07:20,860 --> 00:07:22,930
and just writes some answer without the work.

120
00:07:23,530 --> 00:07:25,270
Naturally, the answer is wrong.

121
00:07:26,140 --> 00:07:29,230
Every time I see it, I get sharp pains in my stomach.

122
00:07:32,330 --> 00:07:37,910
But then when I saw all the mistakes that the answers were derived from, my head started pounding.

123
00:07:39,060 --> 00:07:39,870
And then...

124
00:07:43,160 --> 00:07:45,800
If you don't get it just leave the space blank!

125
00:07:51,250 --> 00:07:55,700
